\title{Ask Questions If Underspecified}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Clarify requirements before implementing. Use when serious doubts arise.}

\subtree{
\title{Ask Questions If Underspecified}
\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\p{Use this skill when a request has multiple plausible interpretations or key details (objective, scope, constraints, environment, or safety) are unclear.}
}

\subtree{
\title{When NOT to Use}
\p{Do not use this skill when the request is already clear, or when a quick, low-risk discovery read can answer the missing details.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Goal}
\p{Ask the minimum set of clarifying questions needed to avoid wrong work; do not start implementing until the must-have questions are answered (or the user explicitly approves proceeding with stated assumptions).}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow}
\subtree{
\title{1) Decide whether the request is underspecified}
\p{Treat a request as underspecified if after exploring how to perform the work, some or all of the following are not clear:}

\ul{
\li{Define the objective (what should change vs stay the same)}
\li{Define "done" (acceptance criteria, examples, edge cases)}
\li{Define scope (which files/components/users are in/out)}
\li{Define constraints (compatibility, performance, style, deps, time)}
\li{Identify environment (language/runtime versions, OS, build/test runner)}
\li{Clarify safety/reversibility (data migration, rollout/rollback, risk)}
}

\p{If multiple plausible interpretations exist, assume it is underspecified.}
}

\subtree{
\title{2) Ask must-have questions first (keep it small)}
\p{Ask 1-5 questions in the first pass. Prefer questions that eliminate whole branches of work.}

\p{Make questions easy to answer:}

\ul{
\li{Optimize for scannability (short, numbered questions; avoid paragraphs)}
\li{Offer multiple-choice options when possible}
\li{Suggest reasonable defaults when appropriate (mark them clearly as the default/recommended choice; bold the recommended choice in the list, or if you present options in a code block, put a bold "Recommended" line immediately above the block and also tag defaults inside the block)}
\li{Include a fast-path response (e.g., reply \code{\startverb defaults\stopverb} to accept all recommended/default choices)}
\li{Include a low-friction "not sure" option when helpful (e.g., "Not sure - use default")}
\li{Separate "Need to know" from "Nice to know" if that reduces friction}
\li{Structure options so the user can respond with compact decisions (e.g., \code{\startverb 1b 2a 3c\stopverb}); restate the chosen options in plain language to confirm}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{3) Pause before acting}
\p{Until must-have answers arrive:}

\ul{
\li{Do not run commands, edit files, or produce a detailed plan that depends on unknowns}
\li{Do perform a clearly labeled, low-risk discovery step only if it does not commit you to a direction (e.g., inspect repo structure, read relevant config files)}
}

\p{If the user explicitly asks you to proceed without answers:}

\ul{
\li{State your assumptions as a short numbered list}
\li{Ask for confirmation; proceed only after they confirm or correct them}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{4) Confirm interpretation, then proceed}
\p{Once you have answers, restate the requirements in 1-3 sentences (including key constraints and what success looks like), then start work.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Question templates}
\ul{
\li{"Before I start, I need: (1) ..., (2) ..., (3) .... If you don't care about (2), I will assume ...."}
\li{"Which of these should it be? A) ... B) ... C) ... (pick one)"}
\li{"What would you consider 'done'? For example: ..."}
\li{"Any constraints I must follow (versions, performance, style, deps)? If none, I will target the existing project defaults."}
\li{Use numbered questions with lettered options and a clear reply format}
}

\pre{\startverb
1) Scope?
a) Minimal change (default)
b) Refactor while touching the area
c) Not sure - use default
2) Compatibility target?
a) Current project defaults (default)
b) Also support older versions: <specify>
c) Not sure - use default

Reply with: defaults (or 1a 2a)
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Anti-patterns}
\ul{
\li{Don't ask questions you can answer with a quick, low-risk discovery read (e.g., configs, existing patterns, docs).}
\li{Don't ask open-ended questions if a tight multiple-choice or yes/no would eliminate ambiguity faster.}
}
}
}